Pre-heat your oven to 180 degrees and boil a #pot{} of water. Peel the @potato{1} and chop into 2cm chunks. Peel and slice the @red onion{1} in half through the root, then slice into thin half moons. Slice the @baby gem lettuce{1} in half lengthways.

Wrap the @garlic cloves{2} in a little parcel of #tinfoil{} ready to roast.

> If you don't have tinfoil don't worry, you can roast the garlic in its skin.

Put the @British Cumberland sausages{2} and garlic on a #baking tray{}, then pop onto the top shelf of your oven to cook for ~{25%minutes} (turning occasionally). Cook your potato in the #pot{} of boiling water.

> Your potato is cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Put a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium-low heat. Add a splash of @olive oil{a splash}, your onion, a sprinkle of @?sugar{a sprinkle} (if you have some), a @salt{pinch}, a good grind of @black pepper{a good grind} and the @rosemary{1/2}. Cook gently for ~{20%minutes} until soft.

Mix the @cornflour{1/2} with a splash of @water{100%ml} to make a nice smooth paste and keep to the side - we'll add it to the gravy later to thicken it.

Put another #frying pan{} on medium-high heat with a drizzle of @olive oil{a drizzle}. Once hot, place your @baby gem lettuce{1/2}(sliced) in the pan, sliced-side down. Fry for ~{3-4%minutes} or until lightly browned.

Once your onion is soft turn the heat up to medium. Add in the water (amount specified in the ingredient list) and the @chicken stock pot{1/2} and bring to a simmer. Stir in your cornflour mixture and simmer gently until it thickens, before turning off the heat, this is your red onion gravy!

Once cooked, drain your potato and put back in the pot with the @milk{2%tbsp}, a knob of @?butter{1%knob} (if you have some) and a @salt{pinch}. Squeeze your roasted garlic out of its skin and put this in the pot too. Mash everything together until you have nice lump-free mash.

Spoon your mash onto plates, top with your sausage and pour over your red onion gravy.

> Don't forget to take the rosemary out of the gravy before serving.

Serve your baby gem lettuce on the side. Perfection needn't be complicated.